Event & Broadcast Performance Report

This interactive report looks into the live broadcast of the Daytona 500 Event during the 2025 NASCAR Cup Series on February 16\.  It includes statistics based on how many views the event received, how long it ran for, the top 5 most impactful moments, the highest-selling products, how fan attention varied during and after the event, and how the event’s performance varied based on venues, channels, and social media platforms.

1. Total Views and Event Duration

The 2025 Daytona 500 race lasted for a total of 3 hours, 53 minutes and 26 seconds and was the most viewed race in the entire season so far, earning a total of 6.761 million views.  Compared to last year’s Daytona 500 event, which only received 5.964 million views, this meant that there was a 13.36% increase in views from 2024 to 2025\.  With the overall 2025 NASCAR Cup Series having a total view count of 69.616 million views, this means that the Daytona 500 event accounted for nearly 10% of all views.

2. Top 5 (possibly sponsor-aligned) peak attention moments.

	The 2025 Daytona 500 Race was full of unforgettable events.  However, 5 moments stood out as being more impactful than the rest, including Logano’s wreck, Preece’s flip, Herbst’s save on the final lap, and a crashout on the final lap, which caused the unpredictable finish of Byron barely scoring back-to-back wins on Daytona 500, all of which happened within the last 15 laps of the race.  Unfortunately, none of these moments were sponsor-aligned.  
![][image3]  
![][image4]

3. Fan attention during the event (Live) compared to after the event (replaying)

	Between Live and Replay content, fan attention was extremely high when watching the race live, as the total number of live views peaked at 7.959 million.  Replay content on the other hand, had significantly less fan attention, as the entire race only received around 285 thousand views on YouTube, along with 1.1 million views when only re-watching the race’s highlights.  In other words, viewing the race live generates higher levels of attention across fans.  Replaying the race on platforms like YouTube, on the other hand, do help people relive moments and accommodate those who missed the live race, but they don’t share the same level of attention as if watching the race live.   These trends align with broader sports consumption habits across viewers: watching events live remains king, while replaying events is supportive.

![][image5]

4. Highest-Selling products in-venue and during sponsorship promotions

	The products that sold the most in-venue are as follows:

* NASCAR-branded T-shirts (e.g., “ghost tee”)  
* Twill jackets & heavyweight hoodies  
* Collectibles like helmets and Galaxy-coat die-casts  
* Elevated offerings from 47 Brand and lululemon

Specifically, NASCAR-branded gear and items topped overall in-venue sales and saw an increase by 23% compared to sales in 2023\. Key items from the Daytona 500 event line also saw a 12% increase compared to 2023 sales, including the “ghost tee”, twill jackets, and heavyweight hoodies.  On top of NASCAR gear and wearables, novelty items, including full-sized and mini-sized helmets and 1:24 scale die-cast models with a Galaxy coat finish were also popular. Lastly, merchandise from upscale and lifestyle brands also received .  For example, 47 Brand operated a mobile-themed shop and saw strong demand.  A new lululemon NASCAR-branded apparel line particularly stimulated growth in women’s merchandise by 21% over several years.  
	As for sponsor-promoted products, there is little to no data on which ones sold the most.  However, one thing is for certain: Goodyear was the event’s premier sponsor and official tire supplier.  During the event Goodyear significantly contributed to the total sponsorship revenue of $388.2 million.  Specifically, Goodyear has an estimated revenue of around $125 million dollars, which is around ⅓ of the total sponsorship revenue during the 2025 Daytona 500 race.  Unfortunately, there is no data on branded product sales, such as tire-themed items.

5. Variance in Venue, Channel, and platform Performance

	As stated previously, the live event, broadcast by FOX, received an average view count of 6.761 million views with a maximum view count of 7.959 million between 2:05 and 2:15 PM.  However, other venues and channels, including FS1, The CW and Xfinity, also had significant increases in viewership compared to 2024\.  Specifically, The Cup Series Qualifying event received around 916000 views, a 12% increase compared to 2024; The Daytona Duels received around 1.84 million views, a 12% increase from 2024, and the Xfinity Series Event received around 1.8 million views, nearly double that of 2024 (934,000).  
![][image9]  
	For social media platforms, the race’s performance varied drastically based on popularity, interactivity, engagement, and impact.  For example, according to Jayski’s digital metrics, nearly 4 million people have visited all of NASCAR’s digital sites (a 30% increase from 2024.), 14.5 million people have visited NASCAR’s official website, all of NASCAR’s videos received 791,000 views (a 39% increase from 2024), and 25,000 users (a 25% increase from 2024\) have visited the NASCAR app a total of 80,000 times with 7400 new downloads.  
	![][image10]  
![][image11]  
![][image12]  
NASCAR’s Live Leaderboard feature also received over 1 million visits with a total of 4 million page views.  On top of the Live Leaderboard, NASCAR’s one-and-done fantasy game, “36’ for 36’’ had over 130,000 unique participants (a 30% increase from 2024\) with over 30,000 entries (a 33% increase from 2024).  Lastly, NASCAR’s Scanner Audio received 340,000 visits during the race and 650,000 over the weekend via NASCAR Mobile.  
![][image13]  
![][image14]  
![][image15]

	During the Daytona 500 week (February 9-17), other Social Media Platforms received a total of 222 million impressions with 65 million on race day alone (a 17% increase from 2024), 4 million total engagements, 118 million total video views, and an Earned Media Value (EMV) of $6.6 million.  
![][image16]  
	When it comes to Influencers and Creator Content, 11 creators generated 93 pieces of content, totaling 7.8 million impressions, 3.7 million video views, and 627K engagements; Collaboration with “The Rizzler” produced 1.55 million impressions and 696K video views.  Overall, influencer efforts delivered 90 million impressions and $4 million in earned media value (EMV).  
	NASCAR even created their own Roblox event for the Daytona 500 race via Roblox’s “Driving Empire”, which received 3 million visits in 2 days, had 2.2 million completed races, 27 million minutes of engagement time, and a total of 139 million impressions (112 million in-game, 28 million on the Roblox Platform).  
![][image17]  
	Lastly, the Daytona 500 was streamed live via Xtadium on Meta Quest VR, making it the most-watched authenticated, subscription-based event on the platform.  The race was also shown at  Cosm shared-reality venues in Dallas and Los Angeles—making it the most-watched immersive race ever.  Unfortunately, there is no data regarding how many people watched the race on these platforms.
